title: For Sale:  Action Arms Israeli Military Industries (IMI) Uzi Pistol Model 9mm NIB Pre-Ban
postcontent:
Few were manufactured between 1983 to early 1989
 This is the 9mm version and comes in hard plastic case and sleeve
 Description 
Imported by Action Arms the Israeli Military Industries (IMI) Uzi was a revolutionary weapon in that it was the first to use a telescoping bolt design, in which the bolt wraps around the breech end of the barrel. This allows the barrel to be moved far back into the receiver and the magazine to be housed in the pistol grip. The Uzi uses an open bolt, blowback-operated design. The open bolt design exposes the breech end of the barrel, and improves cooling during periods of continuous fire. Used by the Secret Service from the 1960s until the 1990s, the Uzi is known as one of the most compact, yet versatile, personal defense weapons of the past forty years. This Uzi is a new in box pre-ban Pistol Model in 9mm. It's been stored and is in excellent condition. The gun pictured may have a different serial number, but is a NIB Uzi. 
The UZI pistol was developed by Israel Military Industries (now IWI Ltd) during early 1980s from the famous Micro-UZI submachine gun. Intended users for the UZI pistol were various security agencies and services which wanted a high-capacity semi-automatic pistol, and civilian shooters (mostly in USA) which also wanted such gun with "cool Uzi style". Despite somewhat rough appearance UZI pistols were reliable and quite accurate. It also must be noted that 'original' UZI pistols should not be confused with full-size weapons based on semi-automatic only full-size Uzi carbines but without the shoulder stock. 
UZI pistol is blowback-operated semi-automatic weapon which fires from closed bolt. It has a stamped steel receiver and the bolt is fully enclosed inside. Bolt is of 'telescoped' design, that is, it is hollow in the front and encloses the rear part of the barrel when in battery. Uzi pistol has a single action trigger and utilizes an internal sliding striker (firing pin). Manual safety of sliding type, and is located above the grip on the left side of the gun. Magazines are of double stack design, interchangeable with other guns of Uzi family (in 9mm caliber). Sights are of open type, with flip-up rear sight, adjustable for windage. The guns were manufactured and fully assembled in Israel. Action Arms imported them as complete guns. You'll get the highest quality UZI Pistol you can get. 

 Details:
• Semi-auto carbine
• 4.5" barrel
• Baked enamel black finish over phosphated (parkerized) base
• 25 round mag
• Original sling
• Original molded plastic and cardboard boxes
• Bayonet lug
• Includes case, cover sleeve, all original literature and accessories 
Quick release clip

title: For Sale:  MilDot Master w/ Manual - $24
postcontent:
The Mildot Master® is an analog calculator designed along the principle of a slide rule, utilizing logarithmic and inverse logarithmic scales developed specifically for performing the following operations:

Rapid and simple calculation of range to target, based on a measurement of the target with a mildot reticle, by aligning the estimated target size directly opposite the mildot measurement, and then reading the range at an index mark.

Rapid and simple calculation of the amount of sight correction necessary to compensate for bullet drop and/or wind drift for a given range, enabling the shooter to determine either the equivalent telescopic sight adjustment (minute-of-angle, or MOA) or the equivalent hold-over (mils), by reading equivalents in both MOA and mils directly opposite the bullet drop/wind drift figure.

Additionally, angle of fire for uphill or downhill shots can be accurately measured, and the up/down compensation can be closely calculated to reduce the errors such shots can induce.

postcontent:
This rifle will be sold at auction with no reserve:  www.octobergunaction.com

Bid Live:  White River Conference Center at Bass Pro Springfield- Sunday October 7th, 2012 at 1PM

Bid Online:  Current bid is $10: http://www.auctionzip.com/aflive.html?method=getLotInfo&lotref=099CE10745&seq=106

Bid by Phone: You must pre-register by calling us at REDACTED.

LOT #107:  Marlin 99M1 22LR carbine

I have done more research on this missing serial number and I have learned this was manufactured in September of 1966 (two letter code on the barrel). This was 2 years prior to the GCA of 1968. I understand that in late 1967 Marlin started putting serial numbers on these little 22 rifles. Do your own research, this is not a guaranty of date.

Marlin only made this gun a few years (1966-1978) as I understand. It was styled to resemble the US Army M1 carbine, with eighteen inch barrel, handguard, barrel band, nine shot magazine even with the end of the stock! This was prior to making the cheaper and widely popular model 60. This features a walnut stock VS the newer birch stock. It also has a brass feed tube instead of the steel one found on the model 60. 

This is a fun shooter and a cool piece of history!

title: For Sale:  Action Arms Israeli Military Industries (IMI) Uzi Pistol Model 9mm NIB pre-ban
postcontent:
Few were manufactured between 1983 to early 1989
This is the 9mm version and comes in hard plastic case and sleeve
Description 
Imported by Action Arms the Israeli Military Industries (IMI) Uzi was a revolutionary weapon in that it was the first to use a telescoping bolt design, in which the bolt wraps around the breech end of the barrel. This allows the barrel to be moved far back into the receiver and the magazine to be housed in the pistol grip. The Uzi uses an open bolt, blowback-operated design. The open bolt design exposes the breech end of the barrel, and improves cooling during periods of continuous fire. Used by the Secret Service from the 1960s until the 1990s, the Uzi is known as one of the most compact, yet versatile, personal defense weapons of the past forty years. This Uzi is a new in box pre-ban Pistol Model in 9mm. It's been stored and is in excellent condition. The gun pictured may have a different serial number, but is a NIB Uzi. 
The UZI pistol was developed by Israel Military Industries (now IWI Ltd) during early 1980s from the famous Micro-UZI submachine gun. Intended users for the UZI pistol were various security agencies and services which wanted a high-capacity semi-automatic pistol, and civilian shooters (mostly in USA) which also wanted such gun with "cool Uzi style". Despite somewhat rough appearance UZI pistols were reliable and quite accurate. It also must be noted that 'original' UZI pistols should not be confused with full-size weapons based on semi-automatic only full-size Uzi carbines but without the shoulder stock. 
UZI pistol is blowback-operated semi-automatic weapon which fires from closed bolt. It has a stamped steel receiver and the bolt is fully enclosed inside. Bolt is of 'telescoped' design, that is, it is hollow in the front and encloses the rear part of the barrel when in battery. Uzi pistol has a single action trigger and utilizes an internal sliding striker (firing pin). Manual safety of sliding type, and is located above the grip on the left side of the gun. Magazines are of double stack design, interchangeable with other guns of Uzi family (in 9mm caliber). Sights are of open type, with flip-up rear sight, adjustable for windage.
Details:
• Semi-auto carbine
• 4.5" barrel
• Baked enamel black finish over phosphated (parkerized) base
• 25 round mag
• Original sling
• Original molded plastic and cardboard boxes

title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson Model 1 ca 1875 with bonus!
location: Durham, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Up for sale is a unique Smith and Wesson model 1, 3rd issue dating to around 1875 or so. 

It is the nickel plated model with rosewood grips and has a serial number of 113846 on both the frame and stamped on the inside of one of the grips. The plating has come off on both ends of the barrel (about 3/8" total) and also on the top of the frame it is flaking. It does show signs of use. It functions well but is a little sloppy. Of course I would not recommend firing it. 

The most unique part about this revolver is when I initially removed the grips for inspection. Inside, a small folded piece of paper tacked inside was discovered. It was very fragile due to age but it was a lock of hair folded in a "Hagerty Bros." paper advertisement. Hagerty was I believe a drug store in the 19th century but I believe the ad has nothing to do with the hair. It was just a scrap used to hold the hair.

Also, written on the same grip that the paper was tacked is a name faintly written in pencil. It appears to say "Bock" but I am unsure. I have removed the paper and put it in a small envelope due to the paper nearly falling apart. It certainly could have research potential if the buyer contacts S&W for the records on this SN.

I can meet in the Brier Creek area after 3pm during the week of in NE Durham on the weekend.
